For example, a Parent can have multiple Kids, but the Kids entity does not hold any reference to Parent.
Why Use @JoinColumn in OneToMany?

In JPA, a OneToMany association is by default implemented using a join table. But sometimes you want to avoid the join table and instead use a foreign key column in the child table to link to the parent.

This is where @JoinColumn is useful — it specifies the foreign key column in the child entity table.
How This Works Internally

· The Parent entity has a list of Kids.

· The @OneToMany annotation indicates a one-to-many relationship.

· The @JoinColumn(name = “parent_id”, referencedColumnName = “pId”) tells Hibernate that the kids table contains a column named parent_id, which acts as a foreign key referencing the primary key pId in the parent table.

· No join table is created. Instead, the foreign key exists in the kids table directly.
Which side is owning and which is inverse?

## This is a unidirectional OneToMany mapping.

Only Parent has the reference to Kids. The Kids entity does not have any reference to Parent.

The foreign key column (parent_id) is maintained in the kids table.

Because the Parent entity defines the @JoinColumn on the @OneToMany side, the Parent entity is the owning side of the relationship.

There is no inverse side because Kids doesn’t have any reference to Parent.